nanopores in biophysics and chemistry has made nanopore analytics a highly interdisciplinary field. This article gives a comprehensive overview on nanopore analytics. Previous reviews have focused on DNA sequencing and DNA detection,2,5–11 non-nucleic acid analytes,12 engineered protein pores,13–16 and solid-state nanopores.6,12,16–18 A review covering pores and sensing has been published 9 years ago.19 Here we attempt to provide an up-to-date and comprehensive account which pays tribute to the highly interdisciplinary nature of nanopore research. After introducing the origin and basics of nanopore analytics, the review will cover biological protein pores and solid-state nanopores. We will describe how the pores are generated and engineered to enhance their functionality, thereby highlighting the similarities and differences between the pores. Furthermore, we will show how pores are applied to sense DNA and RNA as well as non-nucleic acid analytes. The review closes with an outlook on how the field of nanopore analytics might develop.
2. Origin and basics of nanopore analytics
The origins of electrical nanopore recordings6,8,19 can be traced to the conceptual convergence of two preceding techniques: Coulter-counting which was patented 1953,20 and single-channel current recording, which was pioneered in the 1970s.21,22 In Coulter counting, microscale objects pass through an aperture and cause a detectable short modulation in the ionic current flowing through the aperture.20 As schematically illustrated in Fig. 1A, a typical Coulter-counter is composed of two electrolyte-filled chambers which are connected via a microscale aperture. Two immersed electrodes and a potentiostat are used to set up a transmembrane potential which drives a
unitary ionic current through the opening (Fig. 1B), equivalent to a constant resistance at a set potential. When microparticles or eukaryotic cells are added to one chamber, their passage through the aperture can block the pore (Fig. 1C) and cause short pulses of altered resistance. The frequency of these modulations can be used to infer the number of particles, while the magnitude of the modulations is proportional to the size of the objects.19,23 The relationship between molecular size and blockade magnitude is important because it holds that individual molecules can be detected when the pore diameter is of similar nanoscale dimensions. In this respect, nanopore analytics represents Coulter-counting at the nanoscale. As illustrated in Fig. 1A, the experimental set-up for nanopore recording is similar to the system used for the Coulter-counting, except for the replacement of the microscale aperture with a nanoscale pore. Given the conceptual similarity in the read-out technology using temporary changes in the resistance, both Coultercounting and sensing with nanopores has been termed ‘‘resistive-pulse sensing’’.19 This term is, however, not entirely accurate as analyte detection with nanopores is usually displayed as current changes rather than resistance pulses (Fig. 1C). Extending the Coulter-counter principle to nanopores has been possible by applying the technique of single-channel current recording. Single-channel current recording has originally been developed to characterise individual membrane ion channels embedded in natural lipid bilayer membranes.21,22,24,25 Ion channels are complex biological structures whose narrow lumen is capable of passing specifically small inorganic ions from one to the other side of the membrane.26–28 Most ion channels are also able to control the flow of ions by opening and closing in response to external stimuli such as voltage, Ca2+, or neurotransmitters. The stimulus-dependent gating is mediated via conformational changes in the protein channel. Prior to the advent of nanopore analytics, stimulusresponsive channels have been exploited to sense specific analytes by using current modulations of single channels as read-out. For example, the neurotransmitter acetylcholine was detected based on the reversible current fluctuations caused by triggered conformational changes in the acetylcholine receptor.19,29,30 Nanopore analytics is different to sensing with biological ion channels. Firstly, biological nanopores are usually reconstituted in artificial membranes,28,31 as pioneered with gramicidin peptide pores,21 or are formed in non-biological membranes composed of inorganic matter or organic polymers.32,33 Furthermore, the current modulations in nanopores are directly caused by the analyte molecules via steric or electrostatic effects. By contrast, the blockades of biological channels rely on the indirect mechanism of conformational changes in the channel structure caused by the specific binding of analytes. Most importantly, nanopores are usually ‘‘blank’’ and lack any intrinsic ability to bind molecules with specificity. While analytes can be detected with biological pores which were designed by nature to bind specific molecules,34–37 it is often advantageous to use blank pores. Blank pores can be equipped with artificial binding sites and can therefore be tuned for a broad range of analytes. The engineered pores detect molecules which bind to the artificial recognition site (Fig. 1D). This sensing mode is conceptually
Fig. 1 Scheme illustrating the principle of Coulter-counting and nanopore analytics. (A) Experimental set up for Coulter-counting or a nanopore recording using either a microscale opening or nanopore (dashed circle), respectively. (B) A transmembrane potential causes a constant flow of ions through a single pore. (C) Analytes which pass the pore cause temporary current blockades. (D) An analyte binds reversibly to an engineered site within the pore thereby producing a current fluctuation.
