different to Coulter-counting where molecules are passing through the pore (Fig. 1C).
3. Pores
3.1. Protein pores
The bacterial protein pore a-hemolysin is currently the most widely used biological channel in nanopore analytics. The a-hemolysin (aHL) protein pore is a structure formed by self-assembly of seven identical polypeptides from Staphylococcus aureus (Fig. 2). The mushroom-shaped heptameric aHL pore consists of a 14-stranded transmembrane b-barrel and a bigger cap region which is positioned outside the membrane.38 The external dimensions of the pore are 10  10 nm, and the inner diameter of the central channel varies between 2.9 nm at the cis entrance, 4.1 nm in the internal cavity, 1.3 nm at the inner constriction, and 2 nm at the trans entrance of the b-barrel (Fig. 2). Several features of aHL help explain its popularity in nanopore analytics. Firstly, aHL has a robust structure and lacks any moving parts. The resulting unitary conductance facilitates the detection of analyte-induced blockades against an unchanging current level. Under certain conditions (e.g. low salt concentration) the current can, however, fluctuate.39 Secondly, aHL does not feature any intrinsic ability to specifically bind analytes. Specificity can, however, be engineered into the aHL pore by exploiting, thirdly, that the channel walls are amenable to rational design using genetic and chemical means.40 A peculiar characteristic of aHL is its sevenfold symmetry. Due to its assembly into heptamers, a single mutation in the subunit is usually multiplied in the pore. This limitation to obtain a pore with a single change can be overcome with a specialised procedure.41–43 A protein pore composed of a single polypeptide chain is the OmpG porin. Porins are pores from the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria. The membrane proteins are usually trimers of 16 or 18-stranded b-barrels44 but OmpG is monomeric.45 This structural feature is attractive compared to multimeric aHL because a single point mutation can be easily achieved within the monomeric pore. The lumen of porins can, however, contain flexible peptide loops which give
rise to undesired gating.46 Another porin is the MspA pore from Mycobacterium smegmatis. It has a short and narrow channel constriction suitable for the sensing of DNA.47 Less frequently used pore structures include the peptide antibiotics gramicidin and alamethicin. Gramicidin channels are composed of two b-helical peptides which dimerise to form an elongated membrane-spanning tube.48 The sequence of the peptides alternates between hydrophobic L- and D-amino acids thereby positioning the hydrophobic residues at the outside of the channel which interacts with the lipid chains. The two helical peptides of gramicidin channels reside in the two membrane leaflets and can dissociate to migrate laterally within the membrane plane.49 Covalent cross-linking of the two helical peptides is possible.50 The a-helical alamethicin peptides belong to another class of antibiotic channels. Alamethicin forms bundles from more than 10 strands which give rise to pores with multiple conductance states in single-channel current traces.51,52 Several other channels of semi-biological or synthetic origin are available but they have, so far, not been applied for nanopore analytics. Examples among the de-novo designed protein and peptide pores13,14 include structures composed of stacks of cyclic peptide with alternating D- and L-amino acids similar to gramicidins.53–55 Within the realm of synthetic chemical structures with non-biological scaffolds,56,57 octi(p-phenylene)-based pores stand out. The rods carry peptide arms that interact, thereby leading the rods to self-assemble into a barrel-like structure.56 Any future application of the synthetic pores in nanopore analytics would likely benefit from the ease with which functional pore properties can be engineered by standard chemical modifications including peptide couplings.58,59
3.2. Engineering of protein pores
One of the main reasons to engineer protein pores has been to introduce artificial binding sites for analytes. Most of the engineering work has been pioneered with aHL40 because its X-ray structure is available, and the pore is able to withstand drastic mutagenic changes and harsh purification conditions.41,42 Three approaches towards creating molecular recognition sites have been developed. They differ with regard to the means by which the binding site is engineered (Fig. 3). The first approach (Fig. 3A) uses amino acid replacement60 or substitution.61 It has been applied to create a patch of histidine residues to which metal ions bind.42 Similarly, a ring of hydrophobic side chains was engineered to recognise the aromatic explosive TNT.62 Alternatively, one of the aHL protein chains was extended via genetic means to generate a specific molecular recognition site for a kinase.61 Secondly (Fig. 3B), nonproteinogenic receptors are covalently attached to the pore via one or more engineered cysteines. This approach has been demonstrated using pores carrying a single DNA oligonucleotide43,63 or a ligand-terminated PEG chain64,65 to capture complementary DNA and antibodies, respectively. Finally (Fig. 3C), binding sites for small analytes such as drugs and organic solvents can be created by non-covalent adapters. Adapters are ring-shaped molecules which lodge inside a pore while simultaneously mediating the binding of
Fig. 2 The heptameric a-hemolysin pore. The cross-sectional view on the right displays the inner cavity (green), inner constriction (red), and b-barrel (blue). Scale bar, 2 nm.
