View Article Online


smaller analytes.66 Non-covalent adapters can optionally be tethered to the channel wall67 but their main advantage lies in the ability to transplant a known binding site into a new structural framework. This has been shown for embedding an adapter originally used for aHL into the OmpG porin structure.46 The approach can be extended to synthetic channels.68 Protein engineering is also performed to delete structural components of protein pores which would interfere with single-molecule sensing. For example, the OmpG porin pore contains a moveable peptide loop which causes current fluctuations in the absence of analytes. This undesired property was greatly reduced by trimming the movable peptide loop with the deletion of amino acids and stabilising it via the introduction of a disulfide bond.46 Similarly, engineering was also applied to improve the sensing properties of porin MspA.47 Here, negatively charged residues were removed at the narrow pore constriction to avoid the electrostatic repulsion to negatively charged analyte DNA. Finally, engineering has been successfully applied to alter the interaction of pores with electrolytes. For example, changes in the voltage-dependent pore conductance were achieved by placing engineered cysteines into aHL and modifying them with charged chemical reagents.69 In addition, genetic substitutions to charged amino acids have turned the mostly non-rectifying OmpF porin70 into a nanofluidic diode.71 The ion selectivity of the OmpF porin was changed by adding two glutamates into the constriction zone of the pore. The engineered construct showed preference for calcium ions over sodium, similar to biological L-type Ca2+ channels.72
3.3. Biological nanopores in lipid membranes
Protein pores can be engineered with atomic precision, but the insertion of protein pores into lipid bilayers is usually less controlled. Traditionally, lipid bilayers are formed across 30 to 100 mm-diameter orifices in hydrophobic polymer-based membranes.31 A protein solution is then added to the electrolyte-filled chamber to induce the random insertion of a single pore into a lipid bilayer membrane, after which excess soluble non-inserted pores are flushed out. This method is widely used and sufficient for many applications. However, it does not give precise control over when the channels insert. Recently, a strategy has been developed to directly introduce single protein channels into lipid bilayers.73 The approach is based on a hand-operated hydrogel probe which is coated with a layer of proteins and mechanically engaged with the lipid bilayer. The methodology has been extended to directly transfer membrane proteins from bacteria to planar bilayers for rapid screening by single-channel current recording.74 The instability of lipid bilayers is another important topic for recordings with protein pores. Ideally, the membrane should be stable to permit hours-long recordings or to create durable sensing devices which withstand pressure fluctuations or mechanical vibrations. However, due to their non-covalent nature, lipid bilayers are fragile and often rupture. The tendency to break can be contained by decreasing the size of the lipid bilayer. This has been demonstrated by using a 2 mm orifice in a polymeric membrane,75 or by forming a lipid bilayer across a 100 to 400 nm wide aperture in a glass nanopipette.76 Chemical reagents represent another strategy to help stabilise membranes. For example, polymerisable phospholipids were used to cross-link the lipids after the protein pore had inserted.77 The stability of the bilayer can be enhanced by soft or hard support structures. Supports made of soft hydrogels have been tested with photopolymerisable polymers,78 poly(ethylene glycol),79 and agarose gel.80,81 A potential drawback of hydrogels is the reduced diffusion and convection-based transport of analyte molecules through the support layer. This limitation can be partially mitigated by using soft hydrogels featuring a meshwork of large holes to facilitate diffusion. For solid supports, several different systems have been developed. One comprises the covalent linking of the bilayer to a support made of gold. The process starts by tethering a lipid monolayer to the support via a spacer unit, followed by the formation of the second leaflet of the bilayer via depositing vesicles which fuse into a contiguous layer. While membrane proteins can still insert into these structures,82–84 the usefulness of the supported bilayer for current recordings depends on the size of the electrolyte reservoir between the conducting substrate and the membrane. Solid support structures have also been implemented without chemical linkage. In this case, porous alumina was employed to stabilise pore-suspended lipid bilayers.85 One of the challenges in this system was to form a tight interface between the membrane and alumina in order to obtain a Giga-ohm seal required for current recordings. This might be achieved by using a polymer cushion between the solid support and lipid bilayer.85,86
Fig. 3 Approaches to engineer artificial analyte binding sites into protein pores as illustrated for aHL. (A) Amino acid replacement via genetic means creates a patch of residues, such as histidines. (B) Covalent attachment of a ligand-terminated PEG chain to an engineered cysteine residue. (C) Placement of a ring-shaped adaptor inside the b-barrel. Reprinted by permission from Macmillan Publishers Ltd.,15 copyright (2001).
