Irrespective of the support strategy, the long-term stability of bilayers is compromised by the diffusion of lipid molecules out of the membrane into the solvent. Recently, this limitation has been addressed by replenishing lost membrane components using a pool of lipids. The lipid reservoir consisted of an oil–lipid mixture with suspended lipid-coated water droplets.87 When the droplets were joined together, the lipid monolayers surrounding them combined at the interface to form a robust lipid bilayer. Various protein channels and pores were incorporated into the droplet-interface bilayer. By applying a potential difference with electrodes embedded within the droplets the ionic current flowing through the pores was measured.88 Based on their inherent stability, the droplets may be used in future as devices for bilayer recording with greatly reduced electrolyte volume.
3.4. Solid-state nanopores
Biological pores such as aHL have the advantage of a well-controlled geometry and chemical structure that is known at atomic precision. Every reconstituted aHL pore is exactly the same. This assures reproducibility between different pores and experiments performed in different laboratories. aHL and other biological pores can, however, function only if inserted in a lipid bilayer, which can present challenges as described in the previous section. Synthetic nanopores made in robust silicon materials or organic polymers offer an alternative. These synthetic analogues allow for long recordings over a wide range of external parameters such as temperature, pH, and ionic strength. In addition, synthetic nanopores can be more easily integrated into sensing devices. In this section, we present different strategies to prepare single nanopores in silicon-based materials, polymer foils, and glass. We cover small nanoscale pores as well as structures with a diameter of several hundreds of nanometres. The latter pores are suitable for detecting viruses89 and similarly sized objects, and provide an interesting intermediate system between the nano- and macroscale.
3.4.1. Nanopores in silicon materials. The first solid-state nanopore used for sensing single molecules was sculptured into silicon nitride using an ion-beam.94 The nanofabrication technique uses ion beams of keV energies which have two opposing effects on silicon nitride. Firstly, ion sputter erodes and removes the material leading to the opening of a pore in the membrane. Secondly, energy input via the ion beam results in the surface diffusion, viscous flow, and re-deposition of materials, which causes the closing of the pore. Using a focused ion beam, a 50–100 nm wide pore was drilled (Fig. 4A, left panel), and the pore was subsequently narrowed with a diffuse beam (Fig. 4A, right panel). The pore shrinking was monitored in real time with a feed-back mechanism, allowing the process to be stopped when the desired diameter was reached, thereby offering a precision of B1 nm. The physical mechanism underlying the nanostructuring method was studied in great detail,94,95 along with the influence of various noble gases on the pore shrinking process.96 Although the method of ion beam sculpting is primarily applied to generate pores in silicon nitride, it can also be used for other
materials such as silica, Al, Cr, poly(methyl methacrylate) and polyimide.90 The second breakthrough in the nanofabrication of single nanopores was achieved with a silicon dioxide system using an electron-beam as structuring tool.91 In the first method, a nanopore is generated using standard nanolithography followed by the decrease of the diameter using a diffuse electron beam. The initial pores are fabricated in 70  70 mm2 free-standing silicon membranes with a thickness of 340 nm.97 The multistep process for the pore fabrication includes the thermal oxidation of Si to yield thin layers of SiO2 on both sides of the wafer, the generation of squares of up to 500 nm in the top silica layer using standard nanolithography, followed by etching in KOH to yield pyramid-shaped holes. The last processing step is thermal oxidation to form a 40 nm thick SiO2 layer. This fabrication resulted in pores with diameters between 20 and 200 nm. Similar to ion beam sculpting,94 the diameter of the pores could be further reduced
Fig. 4 Solid-state nanopores prepared in silicon-based materials. (A) A single nanopore obtained by the ion-beam sculpting technique. An original larger pore (left panel) obtained by a focused ion beam was closed by applying a defocused ion beam (right panel). Reprinted with permission from ref. 90. Copyright 2004, American Institute of Physics. (B) Tuning the diameter of a single silicon oxide nanopore by a defocused electron beam (from left to right, respectively). Reprinted by permission from Macmillan Publishers Ltd.91 The scale bar is 5 nm. (C) Twin nanopores prepared in a silicon wafer by asymmetric etching. Reprinted with permission from ref. 92. Copyright Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA. (D) A silica nanotube fabricated by oxidation of silicon wires. Reprinted with permission from ref. 93. Copyright 2005 American Chemical Society. The scale bar is 100 nm.
