using a diffuse electron beam of intensity B105 to 107 A m2. Pore shrinking was only observed when the initial pore had a diameter of about 50 nm or less.91 Using electron beams in transmission electron microscopy (TEM) gives the unique possibility to image the pore being created in situ during the shrinking process (Fig. 4B). The rates of pore closing could be slowed down to 0.3 nm min1. In the second method of fabricating SiO2 pores, a focused electron beam with a spot size of a few nanometres is used to drill holes in 10 nm-thin free-standing silica layers.91,98 The diameter of these pores can also be tuned by exposure to a diffuse electron beam.91 Direct drilling of pores with diameters as small as 3 nm was demonstrated as well.99,100 Rather than using the elaborate nanolithographic and TEM-based technique, nanopores can be inexpensively prepared in silicon using asymmetric etching in KOH.92 Crystalline silicon etches along lattice planes, and pyramidal indentations can be easily obtained by using a square aperture in the etch mask. Using this procedure, deep indentations in a 105 mm thick wafer were obtained. The wafer was subsequently placed in a conductivity cell to etch the pore under controlled conditions.92 One side of the membrane was brought in contact with KOH while the other side contained a solution of KCl. The transmembrane current was measured during the etching process in order to detect the moment of breakthrough and stop the etching step. The nanofabrication process typically resulted in the preparation of twin pores with a diameter of B20 nm (Fig. 4C).92 While this method is inexpensive it does not allow for a reliable preparation of small, sub-20 nm pores. Representing another approach, Fig. 4D shows a silica nanotube that was prepared by controlled oxidation of silicon nanowires synthesised by SiCl4 chemical vapour deposition. These tubes were also found capable of detecting single molecules of DNA.93
3.4.2. Polymer nanopores prepared by the track-etching technique. Track-etching is the oldest fabrication technique for single non-biological pores. It has been mostly applied to prepare pores in polymer films such as poly(ethylene terephthalate) (PET), polycarbonate (PC) and polyimide (PI), as well as in mica.101 In this technique, a dielectric film is first irradiated with energetic heavy ions. Subsequently, local damaged zones created during the irradiation –so called latent tracks– are chemically etched to obtain pores with desired nanoscale or microscale dimensions. Tracks are typically generated using ions of Xe, Pb, Au, and U with kinetic energies in the GeV range. This energy allows the heavy ions to penetrate a B100 mm thick polymer material, or simultaneously irradiate up to eight foils of 12 mm thickness. The unique feature of this technique is the direct correlation between the number of heavy ions passing through a foil and the number of pores created during the wet chemical etching. Initially, the technique was used to prepare membranes containing many pores with micrometre-sized diameters. Fabrication of single pores was enabled by technical advances in the irradiation step to limit the number of heavy ions to one per sample.104 In an alternative approach, a single nanopore is isolated out of many in a membrane irradiated
with B104 ions cm2. Therefore, the traces are chemically etched, and membrane areas with just one pore are then isolated. The process of identifying a single pore can be facilitated by using a light microscope for larger pores, or by indirect visualisation using fluorophores for smaller pores.101,105,106 Etching is conducted as the second step in the process of nanopore fabrication. It achieves that the latent tracks are developed into pores. The etching step is important as it determines the size and shape of the pores. The main parameters to tune the pore diameter are the concentration of the etchant, the etching temperature, and the duration of the etching process. In order to obtain nanometre-sized single pores, the etching step is performed in a conductivity cell to simultaneously measure the diameter. The etching to conically shaped single nanopores is of special importance due to their unique transport properties. A conical nanopore not only has a much lower resistance than a cylindrical pore of the same opening diameter,107,108 but also shows nonlinear current–voltage behaviour which can be exploited for ionic devices.107,109,110 Conically shaped pores in PET and PC can be obtained via asymmetric etching by placing a highly concentrated sodium hydroxide solution on one membrane side while protecting the other side from etching by an acidic stopping medium.102,107,109,111–114 The conditions have to be adjusted to the type of polymer, and PI pores were obtained by asymmetric etching in sodium hypochlorite with potassium iodide as a stopping medium.115 Track-etched pores are routinely characterised using scanning electron microscopy (SEM), and Fig. 5A and B show examples of conical nanopores in PET and PI foils, respectively. SEM is usually used to image pores with diameters above 30 nm, while pores with effective diameters as small as 2 nanometres107,115,116 are characterised by ion conductivity measurements.107,114
Fig. 5 Synthetic nanopores with a high aspect ratio. Conical nanopores prepared in 12 mm thick foils of poly(ethylene terephthalate) (A) and polyimide (B) using the track-etching technique. Reprinted with permission from Elsevier ref. 102. (C) A glass nanopipette fabricated with a commercially available pipette puller. Reprinted with permission from ref. 103. Copyright 2006 American Chemical Society. The scale bar is 100 nm.
