3.4.3. Glass nanopipettes. The approach to generate glass nanopipettes with diameters of several tens of nanometres uses commercially available pipette pullers.103,117,118 Typically, a glass capillary is heated in the middle with a laser and then mechanically pulled to break it at the narrow neck, thereby forming two open-ended nanopipettes. By tuning the parameters of heating and mechanical pulling it is possible to obtain pipettes with opening diameters as small as B40 nm. Prior to their application as nanopores, glass nanopipettes have been used in the patch-clamp technique for studying single biological channels,27 and in scanning ion conducting microscopy to image nanostructured surfaces.119,120 An alternative method for preparing glass nanopipettes121 uses a Pt wire with a sharp tip as a mould to form the nanopore replica. The electrochemically sharpened tip is sealed completely into a glass capillary. The closed tip is then polished down so that the Pt tip is revealed. Finally, the Pt wire is etched away completely leading to the formation of an open glass nanopipette. Alternatively, the etching is prematurely stopped leading to the formation of a small conically shaped nanopore chamber. The open diameter of a pipette prepared in this way can be as small as 100 nm.
3.4.4. Sub-micrometre pores. While pores with nanoscale diameters are ideally suited for sensing molecules, larger pores with a lumen of above 100 nm are used for larger analytes such as multimeric complexes of proteins. A route towards single mesoscale pores in borosilicate glass coverslips uses a femtosecond-pulsed laser.122,123 Compared to other techniques, this approach does not require masks, etching or high vacuum. In addition, the pores are prepared in glass, which has superior noise properties, and mechanical robustness. The surface of glass can furthermore be tuned by chemically modifying the silanol groups.124,125 Large pores of several hundreds of nanometres have also been prepared in poly(dimethylsiloxane) (PDMS) using well-established lithographic techniques. The procedure involves the fabrication of the negative master of a pore and two reservoirs, and the casting of a replica composed of PDMS. One master can be used for the preparation of many nanoporous systems.128
3.5. Chemical modification of solid-state nanopores
Chemical modification can enhance and tailor the properties of man-made nanopores for sensing. Similar to protein pores, inorganic and polymeric materials are modified to (i) remove undesired properties. For example, solid-state pores exhibit enhanced low frequency conductance fluctuations129–131 which affect the quality of the recordings. This problem can be mitigated e.g. by chemical modification of the channel walls using chemical vapour deposition.132 An additional aim for pore modification is to (ii) emulate the ion selectivity of some biological channels by mimicking their natural design principles. For example, the calcium selectivity of biological channels is due to the high density of negatively charged glutamates at the selectivity filter.72,133,134 The residues are key to the functional design as reducing their number via genetic means dramatically changes the selectivity from calcium to sodium ions. A similar electrostatic basis is observed
for the selectivity of other channels.135,136 Engineering ion selectivity into artificial solid-states pores by introducing negative or positive charges in the channel can therefore lead to ion-selective nanofluidic devices. Finally, (iii) modification has the potential to equip artificial pores with the ability to recognise specific analytes. Following nature’s example on the binding of acetylcholine to the acetylcholine receptor, it is conceivable to graft modular binding sites into solid-state pores in order to make them respond specifically to analytes. In this section we describe methods for chemical modification of pores in silicon, polymer, and glass. We provide examples on how surface modification affects the transport of ions.
3.5.1. Chemical modification of silicon-based nanopores. The surface of silicon nitride nanopores can be tuned by the deposition of atomic layers. For example, a layer of aluminium oxide was grown via chemical vapour deposition.132 The B3 nm thick Al2O3 film improved the transport properties of the pores by reducing the 1/f noise level. The alumina layer also changed the surface charge characteristics of the nanopores. In contrast to the cation-selective native pores, the coated pores were not ion selective. This property facilitates the detection of single DNA molecules. Individual SiN nanopores are amenable to chemical modification with organic compounds. Reaction with organosilanes rendered the pores positively or negatively charged, depending on the type of reagent.137 Given that organosilanes can form molecular aggregates, two steps were taken to prevent the blocking of the sub-10 nm pores. The modifying agent was dissolved in an anhydrous organic electrolyte to limit the extent of aggregates. Furthermore, the chemical modification of the pores was performed in a conductivity cell using an applied potential difference to drive unreacted silanes out of the pore. Silicon nitride pores were locally modified by depositing silicon oxide as a rim around the pore entrance (Fig. 6A).126,138 This important approach attempts to achieve a spatially controlled engineering of the pore wall similar to what has been demonstrated with the aHL pore. A membrane with a single silicon nitride pore was placed in a chamber containing a gaseous mixture of tetraethylorthosilicate (TEOS) and water vapour. An ion126 or electron beam138 was focused on the nanopore leading to the localised decomposition of the precursor gas and the condensation of silicon and oxide. The resulting silicon oxide layer at the rim of the pore (Fig. 6A) was further modified via silane chemistry to attach single stranded DNA molecules. Each modification step was characterised using current–voltage curves.126
3.5.2. Chemical modification of polymer nanopores. Two major approaches can be pursued to chemically modify polymer pores prepared by the track-etching technique. Both methods utilise the carboxyl groups that are created on the polymeric walls in the course of the chemical etching step. The first way to change the surface chemistry involves the derivatisation of the COOH groups via amide bonds using the coupling reagent 1-ethyl-3-[3-dimethylaminopropyl] carbodiimide hydrochloride (EDC).139 For example, attaching diamines to PET127 or polyimide140 pores changed the surface
2366 | Chem. Soc. Rev., 2009, 38, 2360–2384 This journal is c The Royal Society of Chemistry 2009
Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


charge from negative to positive, while coupling of 2-aminoethanol led to neutralisation of the surface charge. This chemical modification has a profound effect on the ionic transport properties of the pores. Before modification, conical nanopores with deprotonated carboxyl groups are cation selective and therefore rectify the current with the preferential flow of cations from the narrow to the big pore opening (Fig. 6B).110,141 After the modification with amines, the pores are positively charged which results in a change to anion selectivity and an inversion of the rectification behaviour (Fig. 6B). The rectification is certainly a consequence of the electrostatics at the channel wall, because neutralising the surface groups e.g. by changing the solution pH leads to linear current–voltage curves. The ion current rectification can be explained by assuming a broken symmetry of the electrochemical potential inside a conical nanopore.110,142,143 This interpretation is supported by qualitative and quantitative modelling using the Poisson–Nernst–Planck equation.144–147 Indeed, the ionic transport properties of conical nanopores can be compared to the functioning of the Schottky diode of semiconductor physics.148 The conical shape of nanopores provides the unique possibility to obtain discontinuous patterns of surface charge. A pattern with radial zones of positive and negative charges (Fig. 6C) was generated in anticipation of the defined ionic diode properties.127 To achieve targeted chemical modification
at the narrow opening of the nanopore (Fig. 6C), a simple yet powerful technique was developed. In the protocol, only the membrane side with the narrow pore opening is brought into contact with a modification reagent, such as EDC and diamine, while the other side is treated with a non-reactive electrolyte solution. Due to the conical pore shape, as predicted from the steady-state solution of the diffusion equation, the concentration of the reagent is very high at the first tens of nanometres at the narrow tip but decays hyperbolically along the pore axis. Consequently, modification occurs only at the region close to the small opening where the reagent’s concentration is sufficiently high. This results in a discontinuous pattern of positive amines at the tip and negative deprotonated carboxyl groups in the remainder of the pore (Fig. 6C, top left). The pore’s current–voltage curve is characteristic as ions only flow in one direction (Fig. 6C, red curve). This ionic diode-like behaviour can be easily distinguished from homogeneously charged pores (Fig. 6B). A similar surface charge pattern has been obtained in a nanofluidic channel149 using a very quickly occurring reaction between biotin and avidin. Another approach towards surface modification of polymer nanopores involves electroless plating of gold, followed by chemisorption of thiol derivatives onto the gold surface.150–154 In the procedure for gold plating, the carboxyl groups on the polymer surface are first complexed with tin. Immersing the membrane in a silver nitrate solution leads to tin-mediated reduction of silver on the pore walls. Finally, the membrane is incubated in a dilute Au commercial gold plating solution in the presence of a reducing agent such as formaldehyde. The gold film grows linearly with time, thereby providing an experimental handle to control the film thickness. The reduction is typically carried out at B4 1C. The slower kinetics result in a homogeneous deposition of gold and avoid clogging of the pore.155 The successful deposition of gold can be followed by recording current–voltage curves. The chemisorption of thiol derivatives was also confirmed using pore recordings. For example, current–voltage curves easily discriminated chemisorbed carboxyl groups from amino groups.156 The chemisorption also enables the attachment of various biomolecules such as biotin. Biofunctionalisation of gold-plated surfaces was demonstrated first using membranes containing many pores,157,158 and more recently for single pores.159
3.5.3. Chemical modification of glass nanopipettes. Surface modification of glass nanopipettes can help tune the ionic properties. Glass nanopipettes are negatively charged, which results in rectification similar to the behaviour of conically shaped nanopores.117 Modifying the walls of B50 nm pipettes with polylysine reversed the surface charge from negative to positive. This change was observed as an inversion of the current–voltage curves.103
4. Sensing and examining individual molecules
Nanopore analytics has been made popular with the protein pore aHL but the sensing of individual molecules with singlechannel current recordings predates aHL. For example, ion
Fig. 6 Examples of chemical modification of solid-state nanopores. (A) A single nanopore in silicon nitride whose entrance is modified with a rim of silicon oxide. Reprinted with permission from ref. 126. Copyright Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA. (B) Currentvoltage curves of single conical PET polymer nanopores with either positive (red curve) or negative (blue curve) surface charges. The insets represent the experimentally determined charges on the channel walls. Adapted with permission from ref. 127. Copyright 2007 American Chemical Society. (C) Current–voltage curves of single conical PET nanopores with patterned walls. The red curve was obtained with a nanopore which carried positively charged amino groups at the narrow opening and negatively charged carboxyl groups in the remainder of the channel wall. An opposite surface charge pattern resulted in the inversed current–voltage curve (blue curve). Adapted with permission from ref. 127. Copyright 2007 American Chemical Society. Nanopores in (B) and (C) had a tip opening diameter of approx. 5 nm.
