View Article Online


channel blockers were detected via the blockades in current measurements of the acetylcholine receptor channel.160 Furthermore, alamethicin pores detected the PEG polymer chains due to an increased noise in the current level.51 While these experiments were pioneering, they do not represent nanopore analytics in the strict sense because the observed blockades could not be linked to individual molecules. Discrete current blockades caused by individual molecules were first published using the aHL pore.161 The protein pore has a constant current level at a transmembrane potential of 120 mV with a positive sign at the trans side (Fig. 7A and B). When single stranded DNA or RNA homopolymers were added to the cis side of the pore, reversible current deflections from the open channel were observed (Fig. 7A). The almost complete current blockades (Fig. 7A, bottom) represent the voltage-driven translocation of the negatively charged nucleic acid strands through the pore from the cis to the positively charged trans side of the membrane (Fig. 7B). The blockadesalso called ‘‘events’’—reflect the passage of individual rather than multiple strands because the 1.2 nm-wide inner constriction of aHL can accommodate only one individual single stranded DNA molecule at a time. In line with their proposed molecular origin, the frequency with which these events occurred was found to increase with the concentration of the nucleic acids. By comparison, the conductance amplitude of the events and their duration—also called dwell time or event lifetime—was dependent on the length of the strand and the type of homopolymer.161,162 The conductance amplitude is the difference between the open and blocked current levels and can also be normalised to the unblocked current (Fig. 7A, bottom). The event frequency, event lifetime, event amplitude, and the event area163 are four key read-out variables with which molecules are characterised in nanopore analytics.
aHL was also used to pioneer the sensing of individual molecules using an engineered molecular recognition site. In this case,42 the b-barrel of an aHL pore was equipped with several engineered histidines to detect individual bivalent metal cations (Fig. 8A). The cationic metals bound reversibly to the electron-rich imidazole groups thereby causing temporary current blockades (Fig. 8B). Importantly, different cations gave rise to different current blockade signatures (Fig. 8C).164 Blockade signatures represent another property that is used to characterise molecules with nanopore analytics. The frequency of occurrence of the metal blockade events and their duration were Poisson-distributed.42,164 This distribution indicates that the exact time point and duration of the binding events cannot be predicted. The degree of randomness in nanopore analytics has inspired the term ‘‘stochastic sensing’’.15 In stochastic sensing with nanopores, the frequency of occurrence of individual blockade events reveals the concentration of an analyte, whereas the mean duration and amplitude of the events indicate the analyte’s identity.15 The term stochastic sensing was introduced to describe analyte detection with engineered protein pores15,40 but is now also used for sensing with non-engineered nanopores.62,84,165,166 These two pioneering papers42,161 on DNA and metal detection jump-started the field of nanopore analytics to grow to currently encompass analytes such as small molecules, peptides, organic polymers, proteins, enzymes, and biomolecular complexes (Table 1). In addition, the two papers epitomise two
Fig. 7 Sensing of nucleic acid homopolymers with aHL. (A) After addition of oligomers of poly[U210] transient blockades in the ionic current of a single aHL pore occur, which are attributed to the translocation of individual nucleic acid strands as illustrated schematically in (B). The inset in (A) shows two typical high-amplitude blockades with lifetimes of 300 and 1300 ms. Figure A was reprinted from ref. 161. Copyright (1996) National Academy of Sciences, USA. Figure B was reprinted from ref. 162 with permission from Elsevier.
Fig. 8 Detection of metal ions with an aHL pore carrying a genetically engineered binding site composed of four histidines on one of the seven pore subunits. (A) View of the b-barrel with the histidine residues. (B) The single-channel current traces show the dependence of the blockade on the concentration of Zn(II). Reprinted from ref. 42. Copyright (1997), with permission from Elsevier. (C) Binding events for Zn(II), Co(II), and Cd(II) have different current signatures. Reprinted by permission from Macmillan Publishers Ltd.164 Copyright (2000).
