different approaches to the sensing of analytes. The two modes are based on (i) the passage of molecules through a non-engineered pore or (ii) the binding of analytes to an engineered molecular recognition site within the pore. In the following, we will organise the wealth of studies on nanopore analytics (Table 1) according to the use of non-engineered (sections 4.1 to 4.3) and engineered pores (sections 4.4. and 4.5). We wish, however, to point out that this categorisation does not imply that blank nanopores are only used in the Coulter mode, or that sensing via molecular recognition sites always requires an engineered pore. Indeed, we will see that the distinction between the passage and the binding of an analyte can be fuzzy. The distinction between Coulter-mode and molecular binding mode is therefore not always clear.
4.1. Sensing of DNA and RNA with non-engineered aHL
The first report on the translocation of nucleic acids through aHL161 raised the prospect of sequencing DNA strands with nanopores.248 The report also led researchers to investigate the physics of DNA translocation through narrow pores, which is a biologically relevant process.249,250 In this section, we first discuss the physicochemical aspects of DNA passage through the protein pore aHL. Secondly, we present strategies which derive sequence information at the single-molecule level. The chapter will be concluded by showing how nanopore recordings with DNA can help study biomolecular complexes.
Translocation of single stranded nucleic acid strands: pore threading and event frequency. The threading of DNA is the first step in the process of pore translocation. The frequency of threading can be readily calculated from the number of current blockades per time. Several studies have measured the event frequency as a function of transmembrane potential.174–177 In line with expectations, the electrophoretically driven movement of the negatively charged DNA or RNA strand was more frequent with higher positive potentials at the other side of the membrane. The increase in the frequency followed an exponential dependence.174 Below the threshold voltage of 50 mV, no events occurred apparently because the electrophoretic driving force was not high enough to overcome the entropic costs of squeezing a polymer into a narrow pore.174 In an additional study, the voltage range was extended to above 120 mV. At these high voltages the event frequency increased with a lower exponent.175 Most likely, DNA molecules become concentrated at the pore entrance and steric hindrance and repulsion limits their threading into the pore. Additional work in combination with Monte Carlo simulations predicted the capture rate at high voltages of up to 500 mV.176 Apart from voltage, DNA translocation has been studied as a function of the diameter of the pore entrance,174 and the electrostatics of the pore.177 With regard to the latter variable, augmenting the number of positive charges within the aHL pore increased the frequency of translocation over 10-fold over the wild-type protein.177
Strand translocation: voltage and length dependence of event duration. The duration of the blockades decreases with increasing voltage, in line with the concept of electrophoretically driven transport.161 The translocation was studied for a voltage range between 70 mV and 300 mV. As DNA strands
of different lengths were used, the velocity nDNA of DNA transport was obtained from the ratio of the length of the molecules and the duration time of current blockades.173 The experimental data of nDNA vs. applied voltage V could be fitted using a quadratic function of: nDNA = k1(V  V0)2 + k2 where k1 and k2 were constants, and V0 indicated the threshold voltage for DNA translocation.173 Further studies performed with long ssDNA revealed a more complex voltage-dependent interaction between DNA and the pore walls. The data yielded a voltage-dependent diffusion coefficient for DNA translocating through the protein pore.171 Further studies investigated the translocation as a function of strand length.161 At a very short length of 12 nt or below the translocation speed was no longer constant but increased with the shorter oligomers.173 Interestingly, the cut-off value of 12 nt corresponds to the length of the b-barrel indicating the influence of pore–DNA interactions and the drag force which is acting on the translocating polymer in the confined narrow pore.
Translocation: influence of strand composition and temperature. The influence of the polymer composition was first studied by using homopolymeric polycytidylic, polyadenylic, polyuridylic, and polydeoxycytidylic acid strands of around 130–150 nucleotides in length.162 The translocation events showed characteristic event times and amplitudes. In most cases a combination of the two features unambiguously identified the type of homopolymer.162 The different event durations were interpreted to be influenced by secondary structures. For example, the high translocation speed for poly(A) (22 ms nt1) was seen to originate when the helical and 2.1 nm-wide poly(A) strand unwinds to translocate through the 1.3 nm wide inner constriction of aHL. In comparison, the unstructured poly(C) helix with a speed of 5 ms nt1 is thinner and does not have to unfold for translocation. The different current blockades were interpreted to reflect the different extents by which the bases block the current flowing through the protein pore. Indeed, pyrimidine and purine segments within single RNA strands could be identified based on the characteristic current amplitude.162,168 Additional work on DNA strands showed that discrimination can be achieved among DNA strands of similar length.167 The group of strands included homopolymers poly(dC)100, poly(dA)100, block polymer poly(dA50dC50) and poly(dC50dT50), and mixed polymer poly(dAdC)50. Discrimination was achieved by using the characteristic amplitude and duration, and the additional parameter of temporal dispersion. The same study167 also examined the influence of temperature. The analysis yielded that the translocation duration of the DNA strands scales as approximately T2. The T-dependence was taken to reflect the secondary structure of the nucleic acid strands which has to be molten before the strand can pass the pore.167
Orientation of DNA and DNA–channel interaction. Further studies demonstrated that strand orientation and the interaction of DNA with the channel wall play a role in translocation. High-resolution current recordings of homopolymers169 found slightly different current blockades and durations which were interpreted to stem from the threading at the 50 or 30 orientation. The strand orientation hypothesis169 was corroborated by accentuating the duration difference by measuring the
2372 | Chem. Soc. Rev., 2009, 38, 2360–2384 This journal is c The Royal Society of Chemistry 2009
Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


translocation at low voltages rather than high voltages.170 In the measurement a duplexed structure with a free 50 or 30 overhang was trapped inside the pore. The aHL pore is able to trap duplexes because the inner constriction is only wide enough to permit the passage of single stranded DNA. After locking the duplex at high potential, the voltage was lowered to allow the strand to escape. The measured differences in the escape time were in line with the proposed effect of orientation, and the asymmetric interaction between the DNA and channel wall was supported by simulations,170 and studies on the voltage-dependence.171 A related approach on locking and then releasing DNA has also investigated the anomalously long escape times. These non-exponential kinetics were related to the DNA–pore interactions.172 Long escape times indicative of DNA–pore interactions were also observed using single stranded DNA. Here, a feedback control system was used to rapidly lower the voltage while individual DNA molecules are inside the pore.251
Sequence information on DNA hairpins and trapped duplexed DNA. The ability of aHL to pass single but to lock double stranded DNA is also exploited for DNA biosensing. In the approach, a hairpin enters the pore but cannot pass until the duplex unzips and translocates in single stranded form. Systematic studies using different hairpins have established a strong correlation between the type of hairpin and the current blockade. Based on characteristic current signatures, the nanopores were able to discriminate between stem length, base mismatches, and loop length in the hairpins.180,183 Furthermore, it was possible to detect just an additional unpaired base180 and indeed identify the four combinations of Watson–Crick base pairs at the ends of hairpins.181 This sensing approach has been advanced by using a machine learning algorithm to automatically classify the DNA hairpin molecules according to sequence.182 In a related approach, sequence information is obtained via the formation of perfect matched/mismatched duplexes between analyte and probe strands.63,188 This approach uses a biotinylated DNA with a bound streptavidin cap. The free DNA end of the complex threads into the pore. The DNA is long enough to bind complementary analyte DNA strands on the other side of the membrane. Reversing the potential destabilises the duplex and leads to strand dissociation. As mismatched DNA duplexes have a lower stability,63,181,186 single point-mutation could be detected based on the lower threshold voltage for duplex unzipping.63,188 The approach can be performed using hundreds of aHL pores in a lipid bilayer, thereby facilitating the parallel measurements of hundreds of analyte strands.190 DNA duplexes have also helped to sense an individual base position in a single stranded DNA molecule.178 The single stranded overhang of a duplex was held inside the aHL pore by the wider double stranded duplex. This arrangement placed a single base position next to the narrow inner constriction, which is the bottleneck of current flowing through the aHL pore. Different bases in the static position gave rise to different current blockades.178a Another study showed that the transmembrane b-barrel of an engineered aHL pore contains 3 recognition sites that can be used to identify all 4 DNA bases
in an immobilized single-stranded DNA molecule. The identification was independent whether the bases were located in an otherwise homopolymeric DNA strand or in a heteropolymeric strand.178b Sequence information was also obtained from translocating rather than static DNA strands.179 In the approach, chemical tags were attached to individual bases within a single stranded DNA molecule. Owing to their larger diameter, tag-modified bases slowed at the narrow constriction of the aHL protein pore. The pattern of modified and unmodified bases gave rise to a characteristic current signal for the DNA, and the approach was used to discriminate between single nucleotide polymorphisms.179b
Unzipping for single-molecule force spectroscopy. In biophysics, unzipping with nanopores opens up a window to examine the energies and forces of duplexes at the single-molecule level. For example, a detailed examination of the unzipping kinetics has provided estimates for enthalpy barriers to the biomolecular transition.186 Furthermore, the unzipping kinetics of individual DNA hairpins under constant force or constant loading rate187 have been measured. In combination with a kinetic analysis using Kramers theory of diffusive barrier crossing, these force measurements have yielded kinetic parameters such as intrinsic rates, transition state locations, and free energies of activation.189 The studies on DNA unzipping are relevant because they highlight the suitability of nanopores to conduct single-molecule force spectroscopy187–189 which has previously been performed with optical tweezers252,253 and atomic force microscopy.254,255 Compared to the more established approaches, nanopore force spectroscopy does not require DNA molecules to be immobilised on a bead, solid support, or cantilever. The potential of nanopores to investigate the forces in biomolecular interactions at the single-molecule level has been further extended to nucleic acid–protein complexes. The
