studies were conducted with DNA exonuclease,191 DNA polymerase,192,193 and an RNA binding motor protein.194 As illustrated in Fig. 9A, the nucleic acid strand dangling off the exonuclease complex enters the narrow pore. Fast strand translocation is blocked due to the bulky protein lodged on top of the pore. As the transmembrane potential pulls on the negatively charged nucleic acid strand, the protein nucleic acid complex is destabilised until dissociation terminated the current blockade. The longer blockade events caused by the exonuclease DNA complex (Fig. 9D) can be clearly distinguished from the shorter DNA ‘‘only’’ threading events (Fig. 9C). Detailed measurements of blockade duration and amplitude helped determine the binding strength between DNA and exonuclease191 and also revealed the stepwise enzymatic addition of bases by a polymerase.192,193
4.2. Sensing of DNA and RNA with solid-state nanopores that lack a molecular receptor
The first experiment on the detection of single DNA molecules with solid-state nanopores was performed using silicon nitride pores prepared by the ion sculpting technique. In the study, a 5 nm-wide pore was used to follow the translocation of doublestranded DNA molecules with a length of 500 bp.94 Additional studies expanded the examination using silicon nitride pores,163,195–203 and pores made in silicon oxide,196,204–208,256 organic polymers,166,209,210,214 and glass.118,257
Measurements on the influence of DNA concentration and transmembrane voltage. The sensing of DNA via the Coulter-counter approach has been examined as a function of the bulk concentration of DNA,166,203 the length of the molecules,195,196,203,205,206,209 and the applied voltage.166,195,197,198,200–203,205 These experiments were performed mostly with dsDNA and showed similarities and differences to measurements with the aHL pore. For example, the frequency of the current blockades scaled linearly with the DNA bulk concentration,166 similar to results on the protein pore.161 However, the translocation time was found to increase exponentially with the voltage in the model system of silicon nitride pores.203 In comparison, the passage time for aHL was inversely proportional to the external voltage.161 This strong voltage dependence in solid-state pores suggested that the DNA molecules interacted with the pore walls.203
Influence of DNA length. Measurements with solid-state pores were performed to examine how the translocation time t depends on DNA length, L. The time t for DNA in silicon oxide nanopores was found to depend on the molecule length according to the power law: t E La where a = 1.27,205,206 although a linear dependence with a = 1 was reported as well.201 This result was explained by considering that the polymer coil of the DNA strand to be translocated through the pore experiences an hydrodynamic drag. The drag force opposes the electrical driving force, leading to slower translocation speeds of long DNA molecules through a nanopore. Further analysis of the length dependence in silicon nitride pores found that t had a power exponent of 1.40 for shorter DNA strands (150–3500 bp) and a value of 2.28 for longer molecules.203 These observations are in strong contrast
to the experiments performed with aHL in which linear dependence of the translocation time on the DNA length was reported. The difference in the behaviour of the solid-state and protein pores can be explained by considering the pore diameter with respect to the width of the DNA molecule. The narrow aHL constriction causes very strong interactions between the translocating part of the polymer and the pore lumen. Hence, the passing segment of the DNA dictates the translocation speed. In contrast, solid-state nanopores are wider, and the hydrodynamic drag on the whole polymer molecule has to be taken into account, which leads to the power-law scaling of the translocation time with the molecule length.205
Influence of ionic strength on DNA detection. Measurements on the effect of the electrolyte concentration were stimulated by the following experimental observation: lowering the electrolyte concentration from 1.0 to 0.1 M KCl increased rather than decreased the amplitude of the current blockades.204 This result, in agreement with predictions,20 suggested that at low KCl concentrations a DNA molecule at the pore entrance leads to a higher number of available charge carriers. These additional ions were soon identified as the positively charged counter ions surrounding the DNA phosphate backbone.93,204,207 A DNA molecule thus changes the ionic pore conductance in two ways: (i) DNA excludes ions from the pore due to the finite volume of the strand, and (ii) DNA facilitates the entrance of additional cations.207 These factors can be described using the following equation:207
DG 1⁄4 1
