where dDNA is the diameter of the molecule (2.2 nm for DNA), nKCl is the number density of potassium or chloride ions, ql*,DNA is the effective charge on DNA per unit length, and mK* stands for the effective electrophoretic mobility of potassium ions along the DNA molecule. The value of the product mK*ql*,DNA can be determined by studying the concentration dependence of DG and identifying a crossover for which DG = 0. Based on this analysis as well as experiments performed with silicon dioxide pores, it was found that the KCl concentration of 370  40 mM corresponds to DG = 0. Thus at this concentration, DNA presence in the pore cannot be detected.
Folded DNA in solid-state nanopores. The diameter of solid-state nanopores is typically larger than the aHL pore. As a result, a DNA strand can thread into a solid-state nanopore not only as an elongated molecule (Fig. 10b) but also in a bent state as illustrated in Fig. 10c and d. As bent dsDNA occupies at least twice the volume of an elongated strand, the possible conformations can be distinguished based on the different current blockades (Fig. 10a). The effect was first demonstrated in 2003195 and further expanded by several
groups.201,205,215
In further work, the duration of the blockades enabled to distinguish DNA molecules according to their length. This detection method was evaluated using a single silicon oxide pore and a mixture of strands ranging in size between 6557 and
2374 | Chem. Soc. Rev., 2009, 38, 2360–2384 This journal is c The Royal Society of Chemistry 2009
Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


48 500 bp. The length analysis was in agreement with the classical length determination by gel electrophoresis.205
Discrimination between ssDNA and dsDNA. The majority of experiments with solid-state pores examined the translocation of dsDNA. Pores in silicon nitride can however be shrunk to dimensions that allow distinguishing of dsDNA from ssDNA.163,196 dsDNA has a width of 2.3 nm while ssDNA is around 1.3 nm wide. The two forms of DNA are readily discriminated with the aHL pore of 1.3 nm limiting diameter. Tuning the opening diameter of silicon nitride pores to below 2 nm allowed for successful DNA unzipping.211 Silicon nitride pores with diameters between 1.5 nm and 2.3 nm were also used for studying stretching and unzipping hairpins.199 On a larger scale, size discrimination was observed in polycarbonate conical nanopores, which translocated linear dsDNA molecules but did not transport dsDNA plasmids.166
Slowing down DNA translocation. While solid-state nanopores can detect and size single DNA molecules, they cannot yet read homopolymeric segments in individual strands. One of the obstacles towards achieving this goal is the very fast translocation of DNA strands through a nanopore. A high translocation speed limits the current resolution of individual bases. A recent review compared various translocation velocities in solid-state systems.18 Several attempts were made to decrease the mobility of DNA in a nanopore. One method involves the use of high-viscosity additives such as glycerol to slow down the
diffusion of DNA through the electrolyte.200 Furthermore, lowering the temperature and the applied voltage were pointed out as other options to slow down DNA.203 It was found that using nanopores with a diameter of B2.7 nm, which is comparable to the width of a DNA molecule, increased the translocation time over 10 times compared to a 5 nm pore.203 This huge increase in the translocation time could not be explained by the increase in the frictional drag, which occurs when a molecule has to squeeze through a narrower pore. Rather, a translocation of a molecule could be envisioned as a process with many thermally activated jumps over small energy barriers, which could lead to a dramatic slowing down of the DNA translocation.203 A new method to decrease DNA translocation involves the technique of optical tweezers.208,212 In this system, the position of a DNA strand in a pore is controlled via a DNA-tethered bead and laser tweezers. This approach was initially used to measure electrophoretic forces acting on a DNA molecule threaded in a nanopore.208,256 The concept of repeatedly characterising the same piece of DNA by ‘‘flossing’’ it through the pore was first suggested208,256 and then demonstrated.212 In a complementary approach,202 the same DNA strands were repeatedly recaptured directly after translocation through a silicon nitride pore. The capturing was achieved by a quick reversal of the transmembrane potential direction. Repeated translocation of the same molecules demonstrates a possibility to trap and manipulate single macromolecules in a solution.
4.3. Sensing of peptides, proteins, and polymers with non-engineered protein and solid-state nanopores
Translocation of peptide strands. The sensing of peptide strands with nanopores shows some similarities to the translocation of DNA strands. This was first demonstrated in a study on the passage of cationic a-helical peptides through the aHL protein pore.225 The peptides with a cross-sectional diameter of 1.4 nm were electrophoretically driven from one side to the other of the pore. The passage was, however, slowed down due to the electrostatic and steric interactions at the narrow b-barrel.225 The resulting energetic barrier for the translocation of the positively charged peptide could be lowered by placing negatively charged amino acid residues at the entry and exit of the b-barrel.258 These findings are of relevance to the biologically important process of peptide translocation and contribute to a better mechanistic understanding of how electrostatic interactions alter the underlying kinetics of translocation.
Unfolding and unzipping of proteins and peptides. Peptides and proteins which are larger than the pore lumen must unfold to pass the narrow opening. This has been shown with b-hairpins229 and proteins.228 In the case of proteins, pore translocation was studied as a function of folding state. By using different concentrations of denaturing agent, native protein as well as partly and completely unfolded proteins were obtained. Completely unfolded proteins led to short pore blockades while partially folded conformations were characterised by long blockades. These results are consistent with the idea that the proteins thread with the free terminus into the pore, but that translocation requires complete
Fig. 10 Detecting the folding state of single dsDNA molecules with a silicon nitride nanopore. Various types of ion current events (a) are attributed to different folding states of DNA in a nanopore (b,c,d). Reprinted with permission from ref. 205. Copyright 2005 by the American Physical Society.
This journal is c The Royal Society of Chemistry 2009 Chem. Soc. Rev., 2009, 38, 2360–2384 | 2375
Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


unfolding.228 In the case of peptides, partially as well as fully folded b-hairpins could traverse the aHL pore even though at greatly retarded speed.229
Translocation of folded proteins and protein complexes. Solid-state nanopores have been applied to detect native proteins and protein complexes without unfolding. The experiments were conducted using a silicon nitride pore of 55 nm diameter in combination with BSA protein (5  4  4 nm).220 Size distinction between BSA and fibrinogen (34  4  3 nm) was achieved with smaller nanopores with diameter B10 nm.221 The larger fibrinogen caused bigger current blockades than the smaller BSA protein. In another study, size-dependent current blockades were exploited to distinguish between BSA and the larger immuno-complex with anti-BSA antibody.218,219 Detecting analytes via the formation of larger immune-complexes is advantageous because the large aggregates produce an analyte-specific signal. The latter benefit was demonstrated using glass pores of 650 nm diameter and the enterotoxin B analytes.125 Only specific large immunocomplexes gave rise to blockades while smaller ubiquitous proteins in the sample did not cause current modulations.
Sensing of PEG. The organic polymer PEG was historically one of the first non-biological molecules detected with nanopores.51 In the recordings conducted with aHL, PEG chains were found to cause increased current noise259 and –in additional studies– defined current blockades.232–235,259 The conductance changes were interpreted to represent the molecular permeation of the PEG into the pore. In support of this interpretation, the blockades were dependent on the size of PEG chain.233,259 Furthermore, the residence time of the polymer showed a crossover behaviour, first increasing and then decreasing with the PEG molecular weight.235 The data were explained with a model in which large polymers only partially reside in the pore, and the out-of-the-pore part pulls on the trapped part, thereby acting as an entropic spring.235 In a recent study, aHL was exploited to detect minor variations in the size distribution of PEG.232 The polydispersity arises from differences in the number of ethylene glycol units in the linear polymer chains. In the current recordings, PEG gave rise to discrete current blockades (Fig. 11B) which stem from individual molecules temporarily residing within the pore (Fig. 11A). The different current levels varied slightly in reflection of the minor mass differences between individual PEG chains (Fig. 11B). Indeed, the frequency of occurrence of the blockades accurately represented the relative percentages in the mass distribution found in conventional mass spectra (Fig. 11C).
4.4. Sensing in protein and solid-state nanopores carrying engineered molecular recognition sites
Pores can be equipped with artificial molecular recognition sites to achieve specific binding of analytes. This sensing approach has been inspired by biological channels which carry ligand-specific receptors to control channel opening and closing.260 Unlike these channels, nanopores such as aHL accommodate a great variety of non-proteinogenic sites. This flexibility broadens the sensing spectrum of pores.
Genetically engineered recognition sites. The first report on a rationally designed biosensor element used amino acid patches to bind bivalent metal ions42 and distinguish between various metal analytes.164 Genetic engineering of molecular recognition sites helped create pores which respond to explosive TNT62 or the cellular second messenger IP3.238
Covalently linked recognition sites. Pores carrying covalently attached molecular recognition sites are a versatile approach for sensing analytes. For example, the aHL pore was linked to a tethered DNA oligonucleotide to detect complementary strands (Fig. 12).43 The reversible binding of the free DNA strand led to current blockades with durations of hundreds of milliseconds (Fig. 12). A perfectly matched duplex blocked the pore longer than duplexes with a single point mismatch.63 This observation was exploited to detect a resistance conferring mutation in an HIV-derived DNA sequence.63
Fig. 11 Sensing of single neutral PEG chains. (A) The PEG chains partition into the aHL nanopore and (B) cause well-defined reductions in the ionic current which represent the polymers’ different molecular masses. (C) The relative blockade distribution obtained with a single nanopore (top) is very similar to a distribution in a conventional MALDI-TOF mass spectrum for polydisperse PEG of Mw 1.5 kD (bottom). Reprinted from ref. 232. Copyright (2007) National Academy of Sciences, USA.
Fig. 12 An aHL pore modified with a single DNA oligonucleotide responds to individual binding events with oligonucleotides of complementary sequence. Representative current traces before (top) and after (bottom) the addition of a free oligonucleotide 8 nt in length (green) in the cis chamber. Negative current deflections (b) represent individual binding events of the free oligonucleotide (green) to the tethered oligonucleotide (red). The short downward spikes (s) in the trace are translocation events of free oligonucleotide (green) that did not bind to the tethered oligonucleotide. Reprinted from ref. 43. Copyright (2001) National Academy of Sciences, USA.
2376 | Chem. Soc. Rev., 2009, 38, 2360–2384 This journal is c The Royal Society of Chemistry 2009
Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


The work on DNA-modified protein pores also proved useful to examine the kinetics and thermodynamics of DNA hybridization at the single-molecule level. The kinetic rate constant for duplex dissociation, koff, and association, kon, can be derived from the two characteristic temporal parameters of the binding events, toff, the event dwell times, and ton, the inter-event interval (Fig. 12). koff and kon are related to toff and ton via
koff = 1/toff
kon = 1/c  ton
where c is the concentration of the analyte. The kinetic constants for DNA duplex formation at the single-molecule level were found to be consistent with established literature values for macroscopic duplex formation.43 In addition, the nanopore recordings revealed details of the kinetics difficult to obtain by conventional methods which measure ensemble properties. By investigating the temperature dependence of DNA duplex formation at the single molecule level, the standard enthalpy and entropy of the interaction could be obtained. In general, pores with covalently engineered recognition sites have developed into tools to study the kinetic and/or thermodynamic data on biomolecular interactions. Examples include the binding of pore-tethered ligands to lectins, antibodies, or regulatory enzyme subunits.61,65,165 The approach of introducing analyte selectivity via chemical modification has been extended to solid-state nanopores.261 The channel walls were chemically coated with multiple copies of hair-pin loop DNA. The receptor was able to selectively interact with analyte strands of complementary sequence. The interaction between tethered captured and free analyte DNA was likely specific as a single base mismatch resulted in a significantly reduced number of translocation events. The detailed mechanism of the interactions giving rise to the blockades is, however, not certain and could represent the hopping of analyte DNA from hairpin to hairpin. In addition, it is very probable that more than one analyte molecule was present in the pore at any one time.
Analyte recognition by non-covalent adaptors. Binding sites for other molecules can be created by non-covalent adapters. Adapters are ring-shaped molecules which lodge inside a pore while simultaneously mediating the binding of smaller analytes.66 The concept was pioneered with the adapter b-cyclodextrin (bCD) and the aHL pore. The bCD adaptor was found to temporarily reside in the transmembrane b-barrel. Organic ligands such as 2-adamantanamine, 1-adamantanecarboxylic acid, or the drugs promethazine and imipramine reversibly bound to the bCD adapter and yielded analyte-characteristic blockade signatures.66 Reflecting the large number of other host–guest pairs, the sensing repertoire was broadened to include organic solvents.237 The potential of non-covalent adaptors has been impressively demonstrated by sensing individual nucleotide analytes. In the study, the molecular adapter heptakis(6-deoxy-6-amino)-b-cyclodextrin was lodged into the aHL pore (Fig. 13A–C).239a Reversible binding of 20-deoxyribonucleoside 50-monophosphates to the adaptor gave rise to
distinct current levels for each base (Fig. 13D and E). This pioneering work is relevant for DNA sequencing. In the proposed exonuclease approach, a DNA strand is sequentially digested by a pore-tethered processive exonuclease. The released nucleotides are then captured and sensed with the nanopore.2 Additional development is required in order to tether an enzymatically active enzyme to the pore, and to capture each released nucleotide into the pore for sensing with the adapter.2 In a recent study, the adapter molecule was covalently attached to the nanopore and shown to enable the continuous identification of unlabelled nucleoside 50-monophosphate molecules with accuracies averaging 99.8%. Methylated cytosine could also be distinguished from the four standard DNA bases. The operating conditions were compatible with the exonuclease, and the kinetic data show
Fig. 13 Interaction of the aHL pore with the molecular adapter heptakis-(6-deoxy-6-amino)-b-cyclodextrin (am7bCD) and deoxyribonucleotide monophosphates. (A) Model of the heptameric aHL pore, in which residue Met-113 has been substituted with Arg (blue). A model of am7bCD in cross-section (red, nitrogen atoms in blue) positioned at the Arg side chains. A deoxycytidine monophosphate (dCMP) molecule (yellow) is positioned so that the phosphate group interacts with the protonated amines of am7bCD and the cytosine ring interacts with the guanidinium groups of the Arg side chains. (B) Current trace from a single (M113R)7 pore at +130 mV. L1 identifies the current flowing through the unoccupied protein nanopore, which is shown as a model on the right. (C) Current trace after the addition of 40 mM am7bCD to the trans chamber. L2 indicates the current level observed when am7bCD is bound inside the nanopore. (D) Current trace after the addition of 5 mM dCMP to the cis chamber. L3 shows the current level that is observed when dCMP binds to the (M113R)7 am7bCD complex. (E) Event histogram of the L3 levels from a current trace of 2000 binding events. Reprinted with permission from ref. 239a. Copyright 2006 American Chemical Society.
