Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


that the nucleotides have a high probability of translocation through the nanopore and, therefore, of not being registered twice.239b
Sensing without reversible current blockades. The detection of analytes with nanopores does not necessarily lead to or require discrete and reversible current blockades. Depending on the nature and the timescale of the analyte pore interaction, other types of current modulation are possible. For example, fast binding and dissociation events can give rise to an increased current noise when the kinetics exceed the temporal resolution of the current amplifier. This has been observed for the interaction of PEG51,259 and metal ions262 with protein pores. On the other extreme of the kinetic spectrum, binding of the analytes can cause a complete current blockade. In one study, a gold pore with a diameter of 4 nm was derivatised with tens of anti-ricin antibodies. Addition of ricin completely abolished the pore current.159 As the ricin toxin has a molecular weight of 60 kDa, it is possible that multiple molecules bound to the antibody-coated pore to completely obstruct the pore lumen. Changes in the current–voltage curve is another read-out for detecting analytes that bind to an engineered nanopore. This approach was demonstrated with conical pores in PET and PI polymer membranes. The polymer pores had opening diameters of B10 nm which is significantly larger than the analyte. The detection of streptavidin, bovine serum albumin and lysozyme was demonstrated. Hydrophobic or electrostatic binding of an analyte to the pore walls led to the reversal of the current–voltage curve.263 Another strategy for detecting analyte relies on the more subtle change of pore rectification. This sensing approach has been illustrated using positively charged drugs and a Kapton pore with negatively charged channel walls.240 The drug was too small to cause detectable transient current modulations, but the electrostatic binding of the drug to the channel wall altered the IV curve of the pore.240 A similar idea was employed in PET pores whose surface characteristics were tuned by direct modification of the carboxyl groups that are present on the pore walls. The electrostatic/hydrophobic interactions of bovine albumin with the pores were studied via recording current–voltage curves with KCl solutions of different pH values.264
4.5. Sensing of covalently attached analytes
Rather than detecting their transient pore passage, individual molecules can also be covalently attached to the channel wall. This approach is suitable to follow chemical or structural changes of a single small organic molecule which fits into the pore lumen. For example, the aHL protein pore was covalently modified with a single photolabile carbamate group (Fig. 14).243 Upon UV light illumination the protecting group fragments, and the pore recordings revealed the intermediates of the decomposition as shown in Fig. 14. The recordings were able to detect the various intermediates because the current depends upon the size, shape, and polarity of the reactants tethered within the pore. As illustrated by this study, examining single-molecule chemistry with label-free nanopore recordings is advantageous because short-lived intermediates
and their kinetics of formation and disappearance can be detected. This would be difficult to attain with ensemble methods or other single-molecule techniques which require labelling. In another study, the light-induced isomerisation of azobenzene was investigated at the single-molecule level.241 Azobenzene carries a phenyl-substituted nitrogen–nitrogen double bond which can undergo a light-induced transition between the cis and trans isomer. When an azobenzene derivative was attached to the pore wall, the two different geometric isomers could be distinguished based on their different current levels. The continuous interconversion between the two isomeric states was observed at the wavelength of 330 nm but not in the dark state. The recordings constitute the first observation of the reversible photoisomerisation of individual azobenzene molecules in an aqueous environment. The approach to follow chemical transitions by nanopore recordings was also applied to other types of chemical transformation such as covalent bond formation.244 Studying chemical modification at the single-molecule level can be extended to other pore systems such as gramicidin.59
4.6. Ionic selectivity of protein and solid-state nanopores
Inspired by ion selective biological channels, attempts were made to prepare nanopores that are selective for simple inorganic ions such as potassium or sodium. The mechanism by which solid-state nanopores can achieve ion selectivity are certainly different to biological channels because the inner diameter of the latter is smaller than 1 nanometre. For example, K+ channels use a narrow passage composed of carbonyl oxygens of the polypeptide backbone.265 A simple way of attaining ionic selectivity in structurally less-defined solid-state nanopores involves the introduction of surface charges to the pore walls. A charge belt can form the basis for electrostatic selection or rejection of ions. For example, a nanopore with positive walls will transport mainly anions, while a nanopore with negative walls will preferentially
Fig. 14 Single-molecule chemistry photoinitiated within an aHL pore. The pore with an engineered cysteine carries a single 3,4-dimethoxy-6-nitrobenzylcarbamate protecting group covalently attached through an oligo(ethylene glycol) linker. Four levels in the single-channel current trace were observed which were ascribed to the carbamate protecting group, the two intermediates, and the deprotected amine, as indicated. The transition from the first to the second level was triggered by exposure to near-UV light. Copyright Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA. Reproduced with permission from ref. 243.
2378 | Chem. Soc. Rev., 2009, 38, 2360–2384 This journal is c The Royal Society of Chemistry 2009
Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


transport cations.136,154,266–270 Historically, this electrostatic selectivity was thought to function only when the radius of the pore is comparable to the thickness of the electrical doublelayer. New theoretical studies show, however, that nanopores with diameters several times larger than the double-layer thickness can exhibit finite ionic selectivity.268 The calculations come from the linear approximation of the Poisson–Boltzmann equation and numerical solution of the Poisson–NernstPlanck equations. It is important to note that the selectivity strongly depends on the concentration of the bulk electrolyte, which is in agreement with the dependence of the doublelayer thickness on the bulk electrolyte concentration. As a consequence, at higher concentrations the ionic selectivity is lower. Several experimental approaches have been developed to engineer ion selectivity into pores. On the protein pore aHL, these approaches include the use of a charged non-covalent cyclic molecular adapter. The ring-shaped cyclodextrin was docked into the narrowest part of the pore lumen, which maximised the effect on ion transport.271 The ionic selectivity of the aHL pore was also altered by covalently attaching positive or negative charged reagents to engineered cysteine residues.69 A complementary chemical approach is the tethering of a single PAMAM dendrimer carrying multiple positive charges.272 Experimental approaches to switch ionic selectivity in response to external stimuli are especially attractive. Using polymer membranes, ionic selectivity was regulated by pH273,274 and external voltage.154 In gold-plated pores, applying positive voltage rendered the membrane anion selective. Composite membranes consisting of amine and carboxyl terminated groups exhibited pH dependent surface charge, that determined which ions can be transported through the polymer matrix.273 A system which is responsive to the presence of polyvalent cations such as calcium, magnesium or cobalt(III) was developed with silica nanochannels.275 Due to their intrinsic negative charge, silica nanochannels are usually cation selective. In the presence of low concentrations of multivalent cations however, anion selectivity was observed. Higher cation concentrations inverted the effect and resulted in anionic-selective channels. The inversion of charge selectivity was explained by assuming a two-dimensional liquid layer which changes the effective surface charge from negative to positive.276 Similar effects were recently observed with OmpF biological pores277 and polymer nanopores.278
5. Outlook
The future of nanopore analytics will likely benefit from research advances in three areas: new nanopore materials and chemical modifications, integration of nanopores with non-current based sensing techniques, and synergy with theoretical modelling. Nanopores analytics has so far been conducted with biological, polymeric, inorganic, and metallic pores, but not with individual single-walled carbon nanotubes (SWCNT). SWCNT are expected to be especially useful in nanopore analytics due to the well-defined and tuneable diameter at around 1 nm, along with a wide body of theoretical
modeling.279–282 To date, studies have been conducted on single multi-walled carbon nanotubes (MWCNT) with a diameter of B100 nm.283 Indeed, isolated MWCNT were able to detect charged single particles by the Coulter-counter method.283 Solid-state nanopores prepared so far do not offer the flexibility of performing chemical modification with atomic precision, as has been accomplished with the a-hemolysin pore. We expect that the research efforts in the near future will be focused on developing new targeted ways to perform chemical reactions on the nanopore walls or/and a new way of nanopore assembly.4,17 Single-molecule detection with nanopores has predominantly been carried out using ionic current recordings. Integration of the electrochemical methods with other techniques such as optical tweezers, offers a unique possibility to measure forces between the translocating molecules and the pore as well as to control the electrophoretic mobility of the molecules.212,256 Another approach involves incorporation of fluorescence methods into the electrochemical sensing. For example, fluorescence detection can follow the passage of labelled compounds through nanopores either by detecting the accumulated compounds on one membrane side306 or by tracking individual molecules as they pass through the pore.307 The pore could also act as a guide which unfolds polymeric analyte strands such as DNA as they enter the pore. This could facilitate the step-wise interrogation of the sequence as the strand passes through the pore. For example, it has been suggested that a narrow nanopore can unzip short fluorescence-tagged oligonucleotides from a longer analyte DNA strands to help reveal sequence information.3 Furthermore, DNA sequences could also be read from non-labelled translocating DNA strands (see below). Improvements in the quality of recordings can also advance nanopore analytics. Miniaturization of the devices and integration into nanofluidic systems is expected to improve the ion current recordings. Progress in nanopore analytics will not be possible without deepening the dialogue between experimentalists and theoreticians. Table 2 gives examples of theoretical modelling on the translocation of polymers and molecules through protein and solid-state nanopores. There is already a clear synergy between the experimental and theoretical efforts. Experimental results have stimulated the development of theoretical approaches that are capable to grasp transport properties of the nanoscale systems. On the other hand, nanoporous systems suggested by theory can help experimentalists to achieve specificity and sensitivity in nanopore analytics. As an example we mention a nanopore sensor that may sequence translocating DNA strands. The proposed sensor has built-in electrodes that are set up on opposite sides of the channel wall to monitor the transversal tunnel current. As the tunnelling current would be affected by molecules passing through the pore, it might be possible to detect and analyse local structure of individual molecules such as DNA strands. Theoretical studies have shown that each of the four nucleotides carries a unique signature of tunnelling current, allowing for a fast DNA sequencing.10,295,296 Nanopores containing electrodes for the
This journal is c The Royal Society of Chemistry 2009 Chem. Soc. Rev., 2009, 38, 2360–2384 | 2379
Published on 15 June 2009. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 3/20/2024 7:35:30 PM.
View Article Online


transverse current measurements have already been experimentally realised.308–310 In conclusion, nanopore research is a highly interdisciplinary and fast growing area in nanotechnology. It bridges biological pores with robust solid-state nanopores that can be applied in sensing and lab-on-the chip devices. Nanopores form a unique platform suitable for single-molecule sensors and for studying chemical reactions, biomolecular recognition, and electrostatic interactions at the nanoscale.
